This can get messier with associated types, as they can introduce lifetime bounds on their own:

``` Rust
trait Foo { type Out; }
#[derive(Clone)]
struct S<T: Foo>(T::Out);
impl<T: Foo> Copy for S where T::Out: Copy {}

impl<'a> Foo for (&'a u32, &'a u32) {
    type Out = u32;
}
```

@arielb1 

> Will associated types not be a problem?

Maybe, but I don't quite see how yet. Can you give an example of where you think a problem would arise? Earlier, you wrote this, but I don't quite understand what you were getting at:

``` rust
trait Foo { type Out; }
#[derive(Clone)]
struct S<T: Foo>(T::Out);
impl<T: Foo> Copy for S where T::Out: Copy {}

impl<'a> Foo for (&'a u32, &'a u32) {
    type Out = u32;
}
```

In particular here, it doesn't seem like there are any lifetime bounds that are not already guaranteed by WF, right?

@arielb1 

So, if we were to impose this rule:

> We can restrict Copy impls in the same way that we restrict Drop impls -- that is, they cannot have where clauses unless those same where clauses are required for WF -- but with one addition: they CAN have Copy where-clauses.

Can you elaborate on how you think this would still cause a problem? you mentioned associated types before, but I'm not quite sure what you meant by that. You gave this example:

``` rust
trait Foo { type Out; }
#[derive(Clone)]
struct S<T: Foo>(T::Out);
impl<T: Foo> Copy for S<T> where T::Out: Copy {}

impl<'a> Foo for (&'a u32, &'a u32) {
    type Out = u32;
}
```

I think I can see what you are getting at, but I think that this example does not pose a problem. It is true that for `S` to be `Copy`, `T: Foo` must hold and (further) `T::Out: Copy` must hold. One might imagine that this allows a `Copy` impl to gain additional pre-reqs, because it now depends on `T: Foo` holding -- except that we already require that impls are applied to WF types, and for `S<T>` to be WF, `T: Foo` must hold anyhow. 

Put another way, if we implemented the non-lifetime-dispatch predicate from specialization, the assumption was always that an impl for a "non-lifetime-dispatch" trait would be allowed to assume:
- the WF conditions for the types in question;
- where-clauses involving other non-lifetime-dispatch traits;

This seems like a special case of that definition, since instead of allowing any non-lifetime-dispatch trait, we only allow `Copy`. Perhaps though this idea of a family of interdependent "non-lifetime-dispatch" traits is bogus?

So, I implemented a fairly restrictive version of this check based on the dropck code -- it basically requires that the impl can only add the restriction that types add `Copy` where-clauses.

