So @arielb1 and I were talking the other day. We think we could fix this in a fairly simple way: we decide (during MIR construction) whether something is going to be copied. This decision is made ignoring regions. Then, if the operand *is* going to be copied, we require that its type implements `Copy`. In fact, the recent move to split `Operand` into `Copy` or `Move` (https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/pull/46142) already does the first half of this. Now all we have to do is make the MIR type checker enforce it. 

@spastorino has been working on just this sort of thing, so I think it'd be a natural PR for him to take on. 

One interesting question will be whether this results in errors in existing code.

cc @spastorino -- all the pieces are in place to fix this now, I think.  We should use this example:

```rust
#![feature(nll)]

#[derive(Clone)] struct Foo<'a>(&'a u32);
impl Copy for Foo<'static> {}

fn main() {
    let s = 2;
    let a = Foo(&s);
    drop(a);
    drop(a);
}
```

we basically want to change this existing code:

https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/blob/5c41fcec4cd6e76180edb088a48914aa71612e5d/src/librustc_mir/borrow_check/nll/type_check/mod.rs#L376-L384

so that it invokes `prove_trait_ref` instead:

https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/blob/5c41fcec4cd6e76180edb088a48914aa71612e5d/src/librustc_mir/borrow_check/nll/type_check/mod.rs#L1486-L1493

In other words, rather than testing that `T: Copy`, we *prove* that `T: Copy`.
